sec.p:
Verifying CQ empirically means deploying parameters to measure how it is expressed, and this is where difficulties arise. So far, as mentioned above, the parameters used in the literature to assess a person’s CQ have mainly been based on notions of effective or appropriate behaviour or performance, which are typically rather vaguely defined as the absence of misunderstandings and conflict and/or the successful and effective achievement of work assignments (Shapiro et al., 2008; Thomas and Inkson, 2004: 15 and 17; see also Johnson et al., 2006: 538). The individual attributes and skills thought to produce effective or appropriate behaviour/performance are, in turn, many and varied. Earley et al.’s (2006) PRISM model, for instance, identifies five dimensions that people can use to gauge their CQ readiness;
4
 while Thomas et al. (2012) focus in particular on two factors as particularly important: ‘information gathering or perceptual skills, and interpersonal or relationship skills’. However, the parameters used to define CQ and the skills presumed to produce culturally intelligent behaviour still seem too vague to be easily operationalized for the purposes of testing. Defining CQ in relation to such parameters is furthermore vastly complicated by many other factors that might intervene to produce effective or appropriate behaviours in a given situation (Johnson et al., 2006: 538; Thomas et al., 2008). Economic factors may, for instance, preclude effective business solutions even among highly culturally intelligent people.
